    <h1 class="small-width slide-in-from-left animate">CarbonNanotubes.org</h1>
    <h1 class="normal-width slide-in-from-left animate"><span id="carbon">carbon</span><span id="nanotubes">nanotubes</span><span id="org">org</span></h1>
    <p class="subtitle slide-in-from-left animate">The Strongest Material On Earth</p>
  </section>

  <section class="right" id="banner">
    <!-- <p class="caption">raw, dispersed carbon nanotubes</p> -->
  </section>

  <section class="left">
    <h2 class="slide-in-from-left animate">Long Carbon Nanotubes For Composites</h2>
  </section>

  <section class="right">
    <p class="slide-in-from-right animate"><strong>At 30 times stronger than kevlar,</strong> our long carbon nanotubes are dispersed, workable, and ready for mixing into epoxies and composities.</p>
    <img class="slide-in-from-right animate" src={CntPolyesterMix} alt="">
    <p class="slide-in-from-right animate"><strong>Short carbon nanotubes (&lt;100 microns) pull out</strong> of expoxies and other materials. Long (1 mm to 2 cm), strong carbon nanotubes form a complete, intertwined mesh of support and can not pull out. Their strength is transferred to the matrix making it stiffer and stronger.</p>
